			<h2>Organizational Structure</h2>
			<p>While making a loan on Kiva may seem like a simple thing, there’s a lot that goes on behind the scenes. As such, Kiva is structured as 3 separate entities:
				<ul id="entities">
					<li><b>Kiva Microfunds</b> is a California non-profit registered as a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization. Any donations made to Kiva's operating expenses go to support Kiva Microfunds, which are used to cover the costs of running Kiva.</li>
					<li><b>Kiva User Funds LLC</b> holds all funds belonging to Kiva users. This escrow-like account is a FDIC insured, low-yielding FBO account, which was set up to ensure Kiva users’ funds (meant for lending) are fully separate from Kiva’s operational funds and protected.</li>
					<li><b>Kiva-DAF LLC</b> is a third entity that was created to operate donor advised funds to facilitate lending on Kiva's platform for Kiva's institutional partners (such as charitable foundations).</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
